WEBVTT

00:00:07.516 --> 00:00:16.500 A:middle
[ Background Sounds ]

00:00:23.516 --> 00:00:25.696 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:00:26.196 --> 00:00:27.106 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hello, everyone.

00:00:27.946 --> 00:00:30.926 A:middle
My name is Georgios Kontaxis and

00:00:30.926 --> 00:00:32.696 A:middle
together with Katie Skinner, we

00:00:32.696 --> 00:00:34.746 A:middle
are both very excited to be here

00:00:34.746 --> 00:00:36.816 A:middle
today to tell you about privacy

00:00:36.816 --> 00:00:37.636 A:middle
and your apps.

00:00:38.296 --> 00:00:39.726 A:middle
We are members of privacy

00:00:39.726 --> 00:00:40.736 A:middle
engineering at Apple.

00:00:41.316 --> 00:00:42.516 A:middle
And we work with teams across

00:00:42.516 --> 00:00:44.516 A:middle
the company to deliver privacy

00:00:44.576 --> 00:00:45.556 A:middle
into our products.

00:00:45.966 --> 00:00:47.046 A:middle
Here at Apple, we care about

00:00:47.046 --> 00:00:47.466 A:middle
privacy.

00:00:48.126 --> 00:00:49.936 A:middle
And this quote from Tim Cook

00:00:50.196 --> 00:00:51.216 A:middle
reflects our philosophy.

00:00:52.536 --> 00:00:55.446 A:middle
We believe that privacy is a

00:00:56.266 --> 00:00:59.406 A:middle
very basic foundation for a

00:00:59.406 --> 00:01:00.566 A:middle
great app ecosystem.

00:01:01.816 --> 00:01:03.436 A:middle
We think that great apps should

00:01:03.436 --> 00:01:05.266 A:middle
offer the best user experience,

00:01:05.886 --> 00:01:07.486 A:middle
while respecting user privacy.

00:01:08.286 --> 00:01:10.276 A:middle
So, today you will hear some

00:01:10.276 --> 00:01:12.586 A:middle
best practices to design your

00:01:12.586 --> 00:01:14.156 A:middle
apps with privacy in mind.

00:01:15.126 --> 00:01:16.896 A:middle
If you have existing apps you

00:01:16.896 --> 00:01:18.446 A:middle
will be very interested in

00:01:18.446 --> 00:01:20.376 A:middle
updates to our platforms, which

00:01:20.376 --> 00:01:21.106 A:middle
might affect you.

00:01:21.406 --> 00:01:23.006 A:middle
And you'll learn about some

00:01:23.006 --> 00:01:25.136 A:middle
exciting new privacy features

00:01:25.246 --> 00:01:26.506 A:middle
that Apple is launching this

00:01:26.546 --> 00:01:27.000 A:middle
year.

00:01:28.626 --> 00:01:31.286 A:middle
We know that your apps may rely

00:01:31.286 --> 00:01:33.016 A:middle
on user data to deliver great

00:01:33.046 --> 00:01:33.526 A:middle
features.

00:01:34.256 --> 00:01:36.216 A:middle
So, it is important that you

00:01:36.216 --> 00:01:38.676 A:middle
explain to your users how you're

00:01:38.676 --> 00:01:40.446 A:middle
using their data, so that they

00:01:40.446 --> 00:01:42.626 A:middle
understand what is going on and

00:01:42.626 --> 00:01:44.496 A:middle
they feel comfortable engaging

00:01:44.496 --> 00:01:45.266 A:middle
with your app.

00:01:46.406 --> 00:01:47.836 A:middle
Also, you need to get their

00:01:47.836 --> 00:01:49.856 A:middle
consent in the right context.

00:01:50.286 --> 00:01:52.296 A:middle
For example, as they're about to

00:01:52.296 --> 00:01:54.156 A:middle
use a feature that relies on

00:01:54.156 --> 00:01:56.096 A:middle
their data.

00:01:56.096 --> 00:01:59.216 A:middle
iOS has built in mediation

00:01:59.216 --> 00:02:01.806 A:middle
mechanisms for transparency and

00:02:01.806 --> 00:02:02.156 A:middle
consent.

00:02:03.316 --> 00:02:05.716 A:middle
And you should consider how you

00:02:05.966 --> 00:02:09.626 A:middle
can best take advantage of them.

00:02:09.676 --> 00:02:12.216 A:middle
iOS also offers users control

00:02:12.216 --> 00:02:12.856 A:middle
over their privacy.

00:02:13.546 --> 00:02:16.176 A:middle
So, your apps need to handle

00:02:16.226 --> 00:02:19.076 A:middle
cases based on different privacy

00:02:19.076 --> 00:02:20.796 A:middle
decisions the user might make,

00:02:21.166 --> 00:02:23.946 A:middle
including changing their mind at

00:02:23.946 --> 00:02:26.536 A:middle
another time.

00:02:26.716 --> 00:02:28.806 A:middle
Here's an example of how Maps is

00:02:28.946 --> 00:02:30.796 A:middle
using the iOS build-in

00:02:30.796 --> 00:02:33.226 A:middle
mechanisms to prompt for the

00:02:33.226 --> 00:02:34.036 A:middle
users' location.

00:02:34.806 --> 00:02:36.306 A:middle
As you can see when prompting,

00:02:36.566 --> 00:02:38.516 A:middle
Maps will clearly explain the

00:02:38.516 --> 00:02:41.516 A:middle
use cases, navigation, nearby

00:02:41.516 --> 00:02:43.736 A:middle
search results, and estimated

00:02:43.736 --> 00:02:44.426 A:middle
travel times.

00:02:45.396 --> 00:02:48.306 A:middle
And if the user chooses not to

00:02:48.306 --> 00:02:49.856 A:middle
grant access to their location,

00:02:50.146 --> 00:02:51.796 A:middle
Maps is able to handle that

00:02:51.866 --> 00:02:53.986 A:middle
gracefully and provide a subset

00:02:54.036 --> 00:02:54.876 A:middle
of its features.

00:02:55.376 --> 00:02:58.556 A:middle
If the user allows Maps to use

00:02:58.556 --> 00:03:01.146 A:middle
the location, they will be aware

00:03:01.366 --> 00:03:03.506 A:middle
each time it happens, because

00:03:03.506 --> 00:03:05.506 A:middle
there's an indicator in the iOS

00:03:05.626 --> 00:03:07.266 A:middle
status bar to let them know.

00:03:08.076 --> 00:03:09.246 A:middle
And they can always go into

00:03:09.246 --> 00:03:11.296 A:middle
setting, privacy, location

00:03:11.406 --> 00:03:13.976 A:middle
services, see that Maps is using

00:03:13.976 --> 00:03:16.016 A:middle
their location and perhaps

00:03:16.316 --> 00:03:17.446 A:middle
revise their decision.

00:03:19.236 --> 00:03:22.256 A:middle
We also know your apps may rely

00:03:22.256 --> 00:03:23.316 A:middle
on identifiers.

00:03:23.646 --> 00:03:25.146 A:middle
For example, to personalize the

00:03:25.146 --> 00:03:27.316 A:middle
user experience, or to keep

00:03:27.316 --> 00:03:28.096 A:middle
track of feedback.

00:03:29.606 --> 00:03:31.626 A:middle
At the same time, your users

00:03:31.626 --> 00:03:32.786 A:middle
might wonder whether their

00:03:32.866 --> 00:03:35.426 A:middle
actions in your app are tied to

00:03:35.426 --> 00:03:36.556 A:middle
their device, or to their

00:03:36.616 --> 00:03:36.976 A:middle
person.

00:03:38.096 --> 00:03:40.576 A:middle
Luckily, there are great ways to

00:03:40.576 --> 00:03:42.946 A:middle
offer privacy friendly choices,

00:03:43.306 --> 00:03:44.676 A:middle
so that users feel comfortable

00:03:44.676 --> 00:03:46.136 A:middle
engaging with your apps.

00:03:47.006 --> 00:03:49.736 A:middle
Specifically, identifiers can be

00:03:49.736 --> 00:03:51.686 A:middle
random, they can be anonymous,

00:03:52.186 --> 00:03:53.276 A:middle
they can be short-lived, and

00:03:53.376 --> 00:03:55.386 A:middle
they can be easy to reset.

00:03:56.206 --> 00:04:00.396 A:middle
And iOS offers built-in API for

00:04:00.396 --> 00:04:02.326 A:middle
you to be able to generate such

00:04:02.326 --> 00:04:03.216 A:middle
identifiers.

00:04:03.646 --> 00:04:05.126 A:middle
So, you should adopt those

00:04:05.356 --> 00:04:07.126 A:middle
instead of building your own.

00:04:07.686 --> 00:04:10.216 A:middle
As an example, consider the

00:04:10.216 --> 00:04:12.356 A:middle
Universally Unique Identifier.

00:04:13.026 --> 00:04:16.206 A:middle
It is a random 128-bit value,

00:04:16.616 --> 00:04:18.346 A:middle
which you can generate using a

00:04:18.346 --> 00:04:19.706 A:middle
swift code shown here.

00:04:19.706 --> 00:04:22.576 A:middle
As you can see, three

00:04:22.826 --> 00:04:24.636 A:middle
consecutives calls using this

00:04:24.636 --> 00:04:27.686 A:middle
API, will return three random,

00:04:28.186 --> 00:04:29.136 A:middle
unrelated values.

00:04:29.926 --> 00:04:31.376 A:middle
And for example, you can

00:04:31.376 --> 00:04:33.556 A:middle
leverage UUIDs to generate

00:04:33.906 --> 00:04:35.406 A:middle
short-lived identifiers.

00:04:35.906 --> 00:04:38.396 A:middle
For example, you can associate a

00:04:38.396 --> 00:04:41.176 A:middle
new UUID with each session in

00:04:41.176 --> 00:04:43.056 A:middle
your app.

00:04:43.056 --> 00:04:45.606 A:middle
Another example is the vendor

00:04:45.606 --> 00:04:46.206 A:middle
identifier.

00:04:46.206 --> 00:04:48.736 A:middle
It is a more stable identifier,

00:04:49.196 --> 00:04:51.456 A:middle
because it is consistent across

00:04:51.456 --> 00:04:53.556 A:middle
all apps associated with the

00:04:53.726 --> 00:04:54.366 A:middle
same team.

00:04:54.936 --> 00:04:57.416 A:middle
As you can see here in the

00:04:57.416 --> 00:05:00.516 A:middle
example table, two apps that

00:05:00.516 --> 00:05:02.236 A:middle
belong to the same team, will

00:05:02.236 --> 00:05:04.316 A:middle
generate the same vendor

00:05:04.316 --> 00:05:07.016 A:middle
identifier, while a third app

00:05:07.726 --> 00:05:08.956 A:middle
belonging to a different team

00:05:09.256 --> 00:05:10.056 A:middle
will have its own.

00:05:11.166 --> 00:05:14.336 A:middle
Also, keep in mind that if all

00:05:14.476 --> 00:05:16.236 A:middle
apps belonging to a particular

00:05:16.236 --> 00:05:18.186 A:middle
team are uninstalled from the

00:05:18.186 --> 00:05:19.896 A:middle
user devices and later

00:05:19.896 --> 00:05:22.466 A:middle
reinstalled, they will get a new

00:05:22.466 --> 00:05:22.996 A:middle
identifier.

00:05:22.996 --> 00:05:26.636 A:middle
Now, let's talk about collecting

00:05:26.986 --> 00:05:28.926 A:middle
data to enable your features.

00:05:29.766 --> 00:05:31.666 A:middle
Collecting data can be a

00:05:31.666 --> 00:05:34.056 A:middle
benefit, but also carries risks.

00:05:35.176 --> 00:05:38.976 A:middle
So, users might be uncomfortable

00:05:39.856 --> 00:05:41.986 A:middle
giving too much of their data if

00:05:41.986 --> 00:05:43.476 A:middle
you don't sufficiently justify

00:05:43.476 --> 00:05:44.296 A:middle
the purpose.

00:05:44.996 --> 00:05:47.146 A:middle
And also, consider the burden on

00:05:47.146 --> 00:05:49.846 A:middle
your end to manage all that data

00:05:50.036 --> 00:05:51.656 A:middle
and keep it safe.

00:05:51.906 --> 00:05:53.266 A:middle
So, you should consider

00:05:53.736 --> 00:05:55.866 A:middle
aggregating data, summarizing

00:05:55.866 --> 00:05:55.956 A:middle
it.

00:05:56.306 --> 00:05:57.426 A:middle
And extracting only the

00:05:57.426 --> 00:05:59.126 A:middle
information you need.

00:05:59.686 --> 00:06:02.216 A:middle
As an alternative, think whether

00:06:02.216 --> 00:06:03.856 A:middle
a sample of the data will

00:06:03.856 --> 00:06:06.926 A:middle
suffice, or whether you can

00:06:08.166 --> 00:06:09.576 A:middle
process the data on the device

00:06:10.526 --> 00:06:12.006 A:middle
instead of sending their own

00:06:12.006 --> 00:06:13.546 A:middle
values to your server.

00:06:14.406 --> 00:06:16.056 A:middle
And later in this talk, you will

00:06:16.056 --> 00:06:17.656 A:middle
hear about some great new ways

00:06:18.026 --> 00:06:20.426 A:middle
to process data on device using

00:06:20.476 --> 00:06:23.966 A:middle
iOS hardware and software.

00:06:24.046 --> 00:06:25.966 A:middle
Collecting raw data might reveal

00:06:26.386 --> 00:06:27.756 A:middle
additional information about the

00:06:27.756 --> 00:06:28.356 A:middle
users.

00:06:28.766 --> 00:06:30.526 A:middle
And as mentioned, this is

00:06:30.526 --> 00:06:32.526 A:middle
information that neither your

00:06:32.526 --> 00:06:34.266 A:middle
users, nor you might want to

00:06:34.266 --> 00:06:34.546 A:middle
have.

00:06:34.676 --> 00:06:36.786 A:middle
As an example, consider you have

00:06:37.246 --> 00:06:39.036 A:middle
a new feature in your app and

00:06:39.036 --> 00:06:40.236 A:middle
you need to collect feedback to

00:06:40.236 --> 00:06:41.706 A:middle
see how successful it is.

00:06:42.356 --> 00:06:44.766 A:middle
So, you could instrument your

00:06:44.766 --> 00:06:47.576 A:middle
app to send back a timestamp to

00:06:47.576 --> 00:06:49.636 A:middle
your server each time users

00:06:49.636 --> 00:06:50.656 A:middle
engage with the feature.

00:06:51.626 --> 00:06:53.726 A:middle
And the app would give you the

00:06:53.726 --> 00:06:54.886 A:middle
information that you're after,

00:06:55.206 --> 00:06:56.966 A:middle
but if you were to plot that

00:06:57.046 --> 00:06:59.146 A:middle
data over a timeline, you would

00:06:59.146 --> 00:07:01.316 A:middle
also learn that user 1 is a

00:07:01.316 --> 00:07:03.376 A:middle
morning person because all of

00:07:03.376 --> 00:07:04.776 A:middle
their timestamps are in the

00:07:04.776 --> 00:07:05.206 A:middle
morning.

00:07:05.586 --> 00:07:07.656 A:middle
And user 3 opens your app at

00:07:07.696 --> 00:07:07.936 A:middle
night.

00:07:09.276 --> 00:07:11.656 A:middle
So, another way to collect this

00:07:11.656 --> 00:07:12.976 A:middle
information would be to say,

00:07:12.976 --> 00:07:15.996 A:middle
well I will have my app count

00:07:16.666 --> 00:07:19.536 A:middle
the full number of times that a

00:07:19.536 --> 00:07:21.236 A:middle
particular user engages with my

00:07:21.326 --> 00:07:23.186 A:middle
feature, and sent that count

00:07:23.226 --> 00:07:24.876 A:middle
back to my server once a day.

00:07:26.026 --> 00:07:28.136 A:middle
And that is a more privacy

00:07:28.196 --> 00:07:30.366 A:middle
friendly way to learn the same

00:07:30.366 --> 00:07:31.586 A:middle
information about the feature,

00:07:32.246 --> 00:07:34.046 A:middle
whether it's successful or not.

00:07:34.896 --> 00:07:36.426 A:middle
But if you pay attention, you

00:07:36.426 --> 00:07:37.996 A:middle
might realize that now you know

00:07:37.996 --> 00:07:40.956 A:middle
that user 1 likes your feature

00:07:40.956 --> 00:07:44.386 A:middle
the most among your users.

00:07:44.816 --> 00:07:46.416 A:middle
And that's not the question you

00:07:46.416 --> 00:07:47.296 A:middle
were trying to answer.

00:07:48.236 --> 00:07:50.436 A:middle
So, if you rephrase the question

00:07:50.726 --> 00:07:53.506 A:middle
as how many users engage with my

00:07:53.606 --> 00:07:55.336 A:middle
feature more than 10 times a

00:07:55.336 --> 00:07:57.386 A:middle
day, you could have your app

00:07:57.876 --> 00:07:59.236 A:middle
send back to your server a

00:07:59.236 --> 00:08:02.076 A:middle
booleon flag, yes or no, whether

00:08:02.076 --> 00:08:03.706 A:middle
the user has exceeded that

00:08:03.706 --> 00:08:04.746 A:middle
threshold within the day.

00:08:06.056 --> 00:08:08.056 A:middle
And on your end, on the server,

00:08:08.456 --> 00:08:10.476 A:middle
you could calculate the percent

00:08:10.476 --> 00:08:12.206 A:middle
of the users that have exceeded

00:08:12.206 --> 00:08:13.716 A:middle
the threshold, in this

00:08:13.716 --> 00:08:15.866 A:middle
particular case, 66%.

00:08:16.706 --> 00:08:18.396 A:middle
Keep that percentage on your

00:08:18.396 --> 00:08:18.846 A:middle
server.

00:08:19.196 --> 00:08:20.506 A:middle
Keep track of it over time as it

00:08:20.506 --> 00:08:22.476 A:middle
changes, to understand how your

00:08:22.526 --> 00:08:26.596 A:middle
feature behaves and discard any

00:08:26.596 --> 00:08:29.576 A:middle
user specific data.

00:08:29.756 --> 00:08:31.516 A:middle
So, now let's go over some

00:08:31.516 --> 00:08:33.746 A:middle
updates, which might affect your

00:08:33.926 --> 00:08:34.176 A:middle
apps.

00:08:35.186 --> 00:08:37.386 A:middle
I mentioned earlier that when

00:08:37.516 --> 00:08:39.736 A:middle
apps ask for access to user

00:08:40.346 --> 00:08:43.126 A:middle
data, iOS will prompt users for

00:08:43.126 --> 00:08:43.616 A:middle
their consent.

00:08:44.656 --> 00:08:46.216 A:middle
And there are cases where we

00:08:46.216 --> 00:08:48.946 A:middle
think that users need as much

00:08:48.946 --> 00:08:50.956 A:middle
information as possible to make

00:08:51.036 --> 00:08:51.656 A:middle
this decision.

00:08:52.466 --> 00:08:55.056 A:middle
And your app is responsible for

00:08:55.056 --> 00:08:56.146 A:middle
providing this additional

00:08:56.176 --> 00:08:56.706 A:middle
context.

00:08:57.646 --> 00:08:59.316 A:middle
This additional context is in

00:08:59.316 --> 00:09:00.646 A:middle
the form of purpose strings.

00:09:00.926 --> 00:09:01.936 A:middle
And purposes strings are

00:09:01.936 --> 00:09:03.966 A:middle
included in the prompt shown to

00:09:03.966 --> 00:09:05.216 A:middle
the user by iOS.

00:09:06.116 --> 00:09:07.456 A:middle
Purpose strings are defined as

00:09:07.616 --> 00:09:10.046 A:middle
keys in the info.plist file of

00:09:10.046 --> 00:09:10.456 A:middle
your app.

00:09:12.016 --> 00:09:15.116 A:middle
And you can define those keys in

00:09:15.116 --> 00:09:15.976 A:middle
Xcode, like so.

00:09:16.526 --> 00:09:20.066 A:middle
Keep in mind that those keys are

00:09:20.396 --> 00:09:21.106 A:middle
mandatory.

00:09:21.766 --> 00:09:24.466 A:middle
So, if your app is missing a

00:09:24.526 --> 00:09:26.186 A:middle
purpose string and tries to

00:09:26.186 --> 00:09:29.586 A:middle
access related data, it will

00:09:29.586 --> 00:09:31.686 A:middle
terminate with an error message

00:09:31.686 --> 00:09:33.816 A:middle
indicating which key is missing.

00:09:34.396 --> 00:09:38.076 A:middle
In iOS 10, these are the cases

00:09:38.076 --> 00:09:39.026 A:middle
where purpose strings are

00:09:39.026 --> 00:09:39.456 A:middle
required.

00:09:40.426 --> 00:09:42.956 A:middle
And in iOS 11, we're making

00:09:42.956 --> 00:09:46.196 A:middle
changes to location, photos, and

00:09:46.196 --> 00:09:47.406 A:middle
we're adding a purpose string

00:09:47.496 --> 00:09:49.166 A:middle
for CoreNFC.

00:09:50.456 --> 00:09:54.026 A:middle
Core location has enabled great

00:09:54.126 --> 00:09:55.296 A:middle
features in your apps.

00:09:55.876 --> 00:09:59.706 A:middle
Users appreciate being able to

00:09:59.706 --> 00:10:03.706 A:middle
navigate the world and find

00:10:03.706 --> 00:10:05.566 A:middle
interesting places through their

00:10:05.606 --> 00:10:06.436 A:middle
iOS device.

00:10:07.076 --> 00:10:10.296 A:middle
At the same time, we want users

00:10:10.296 --> 00:10:12.076 A:middle
to always be in control of their

00:10:12.076 --> 00:10:12.556 A:middle
privacy.

00:10:13.636 --> 00:10:18.346 A:middle
So, in iOS 10, apps can ask for

00:10:18.546 --> 00:10:20.456 A:middle
access to the user's location at

00:10:20.456 --> 00:10:22.986 A:middle
all times, or while the app is

00:10:22.986 --> 00:10:24.146 A:middle
in use.

00:10:24.836 --> 00:10:29.526 A:middle
In iOS 11, users will be able to

00:10:29.576 --> 00:10:32.486 A:middle
choose the when to use option at

00:10:32.486 --> 00:10:33.156 A:middle
all times.

00:10:34.516 --> 00:10:41.236 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:10:41.736 --> 00:10:43.246 A:middle
What this means for you is that

00:10:44.276 --> 00:10:47.006 A:middle
your app will have to account

00:10:47.126 --> 00:10:49.076 A:middle
for cases where the users'

00:10:49.076 --> 00:10:51.116 A:middle
location is not available to

00:10:51.116 --> 00:10:51.276 A:middle
you.

00:10:51.716 --> 00:10:52.926 A:middle
And you need to define

00:10:52.976 --> 00:10:54.556 A:middle
additional purpose strings for

00:10:54.556 --> 00:10:55.466 A:middle
the when to use option.

00:10:56.696 --> 00:10:59.306 A:middle
As a reminder, when asking for

00:10:59.306 --> 00:11:01.226 A:middle
the user location, make sure you

00:11:01.226 --> 00:11:02.446 A:middle
do it in a meaningful way.

00:11:03.306 --> 00:11:06.106 A:middle
Make sure you prompt after the

00:11:06.106 --> 00:11:07.416 A:middle
user has engaged with the

00:11:07.506 --> 00:11:08.566 A:middle
feature that requires the

00:11:08.566 --> 00:11:10.796 A:middle
location, so they understand why

00:11:10.796 --> 00:11:11.626 A:middle
they're being asked for their

00:11:11.626 --> 00:11:12.126 A:middle
location.

00:11:13.106 --> 00:11:14.406 A:middle
When you prompt, make sure your

00:11:14.406 --> 00:11:16.546 A:middle
purpose string provides the

00:11:16.546 --> 00:11:18.406 A:middle
necessary information for the

00:11:18.406 --> 00:11:20.436 A:middle
user to make a good decision.

00:11:21.406 --> 00:11:24.336 A:middle
And if possible, try asking for

00:11:24.576 --> 00:11:26.776 A:middle
When In Use and escalate to

00:11:26.776 --> 00:11:29.126 A:middle
always after the user has some

00:11:29.126 --> 00:11:31.586 A:middle
time to experience your feature.

00:11:32.126 --> 00:11:36.996 A:middle
If you have an app on iOS 10

00:11:37.076 --> 00:11:39.416 A:middle
that does not support the When

00:11:39.416 --> 00:11:41.546 A:middle
In Use option, this is the

00:11:41.546 --> 00:11:43.986 A:middle
prompt a user will see when they

00:11:43.986 --> 00:11:45.566 A:middle
upgrade to iOS 11.

00:11:46.366 --> 00:11:48.526 A:middle
As you can see, they can choose

00:11:48.526 --> 00:11:50.656 A:middle
the When In Use option, but

00:11:50.656 --> 00:11:51.966 A:middle
there is a warning that the app

00:11:51.966 --> 00:11:54.526 A:middle
does not maybe support it.

00:11:57.376 --> 00:11:59.556 A:middle
If you have an app on iOS 10

00:11:59.866 --> 00:12:01.996 A:middle
that does support both the When

00:12:01.996 --> 00:12:03.876 A:middle
In Use and the always option,

00:12:04.486 --> 00:12:05.946 A:middle
this is the prompt you will see.

00:12:06.636 --> 00:12:08.236 A:middle
Both purpose strings will be

00:12:08.236 --> 00:12:09.886 A:middle
included in the prompt shown to

00:12:09.886 --> 00:12:10.346 A:middle
the user.

00:12:11.196 --> 00:12:12.886 A:middle
You should update your apps to

00:12:12.956 --> 00:12:14.336 A:middle
feature a single purpose string.

00:12:14.746 --> 00:12:17.696 A:middle
And you can do that by defining

00:12:17.696 --> 00:12:19.946 A:middle
a single key in your [inaudible]

00:12:20.156 --> 00:12:20.506 A:middle
file.

00:12:20.636 --> 00:12:22.576 A:middle
And that is the always and When

00:12:22.696 --> 00:12:24.936 A:middle
In Use key.

00:12:25.176 --> 00:12:27.106 A:middle
So, now let's talk about photos.

00:12:28.176 --> 00:12:29.366 A:middle
The users photos library

00:12:29.656 --> 00:12:30.986 A:middle
contains a lot of information

00:12:31.586 --> 00:12:33.976 A:middle
and we want you to be able to

00:12:33.976 --> 00:12:35.506 A:middle
leverage that information to

00:12:35.506 --> 00:12:36.516 A:middle
deliver great features.

00:12:37.456 --> 00:12:38.716 A:middle
At the same time, we want to

00:12:38.716 --> 00:12:40.266 A:middle
maintain a high level of user

00:12:40.306 --> 00:12:40.796 A:middle
privacy.

00:12:41.386 --> 00:12:43.816 A:middle
So, this year, we're adding two

00:12:43.816 --> 00:12:46.076 A:middle
new ways for your apps to

00:12:46.076 --> 00:12:47.526 A:middle
interact with the photos

00:12:47.526 --> 00:12:47.976 A:middle
library.

00:12:49.066 --> 00:12:51.356 A:middle
Specifically, users will be able

00:12:51.356 --> 00:12:53.986 A:middle
to open a photo in your app,

00:12:54.256 --> 00:12:55.516 A:middle
without the need for you to

00:12:55.516 --> 00:12:57.296 A:middle
prompt for access to their

00:12:57.296 --> 00:12:59.116 A:middle
entire photos library.

00:12:59.546 --> 00:13:02.956 A:middle
So, this will make them more

00:13:02.956 --> 00:13:04.706 A:middle
comfortable using your app

00:13:05.326 --> 00:13:06.886 A:middle
because they will have better

00:13:06.886 --> 00:13:08.406 A:middle
control over their data.

00:13:09.526 --> 00:13:12.456 A:middle
We're also adding a write only

00:13:12.606 --> 00:13:14.476 A:middle
access to the photos library.

00:13:15.286 --> 00:13:16.916 A:middle
So, for example, if there's a

00:13:16.916 --> 00:13:18.376 A:middle
game that wants to save a

00:13:18.376 --> 00:13:20.016 A:middle
screenshot of the user

00:13:20.016 --> 00:13:22.236 A:middle
achievements, it can prompt for

00:13:22.236 --> 00:13:24.906 A:middle
write, but not read access to

00:13:24.906 --> 00:13:25.736 A:middle
the photos library.

00:13:26.496 --> 00:13:28.456 A:middle
And users might be more willing

00:13:28.456 --> 00:13:29.566 A:middle
to grant that request.

00:13:30.986 --> 00:13:32.176 A:middle
And because of these changes,

00:13:32.926 --> 00:13:37.136 A:middle
when users upgrade their devices

00:13:37.416 --> 00:13:39.916 A:middle
with iOS 11, existing apps will

00:13:39.916 --> 00:13:41.966 A:middle
re-prompt for access to the

00:13:41.966 --> 00:13:42.646 A:middle
photos library.

00:13:43.386 --> 00:13:44.376 A:middle
If you want your users to be

00:13:44.376 --> 00:13:46.506 A:middle
able to take advantage of this

00:13:46.506 --> 00:13:48.896 A:middle
ability to open photos in your

00:13:48.896 --> 00:13:52.336 A:middle
app without being prompted, you

00:13:52.336 --> 00:13:54.246 A:middle
can adopt the added process

00:13:54.416 --> 00:13:56.376 A:middle
image picker, and you find out

00:13:56.376 --> 00:13:58.496 A:middle
more, please visit the photo

00:13:58.496 --> 00:13:58.906 A:middle
session.

00:13:59.326 --> 00:14:03.576 A:middle
This is a great way to add a

00:14:03.666 --> 00:14:06.476 A:middle
photo in a users' profile, or

00:14:06.856 --> 00:14:08.016 A:middle
use a photo in some other rare

00:14:08.016 --> 00:14:08.816 A:middle
action in your app.

00:14:08.916 --> 00:14:11.956 A:middle
Now, this is in the write-only

00:14:11.956 --> 00:14:12.366 A:middle
case.

00:14:13.846 --> 00:14:15.556 A:middle
There's a prompt and a purpose

00:14:15.556 --> 00:14:15.826 A:middle
string.

00:14:15.936 --> 00:14:17.776 A:middle
So, if you want to adopt this,

00:14:17.926 --> 00:14:18.896 A:middle
you need to declare the purpose

00:14:18.896 --> 00:14:22.266 A:middle
string and make sure you provide

00:14:23.106 --> 00:14:24.756 A:middle
enough information for the user

00:14:24.756 --> 00:14:27.216 A:middle
to decide whether they want to

00:14:27.376 --> 00:14:28.186 A:middle
use this feature.

00:14:28.186 --> 00:14:31.516 A:middle
Now, let's talk about CoreNFC.

00:14:32.186 --> 00:14:34.196 A:middle
CoreNFC is a new and exciting

00:14:34.436 --> 00:14:36.876 A:middle
iOS 11 framework, which allows

00:14:36.876 --> 00:14:39.646 A:middle
your app to use NFC reader mode

00:14:40.136 --> 00:14:42.536 A:middle
to interact with nearby NFC

00:14:42.636 --> 00:14:42.886 A:middle
tags.

00:14:43.576 --> 00:14:45.576 A:middle
So, now you can use NFC tags in

00:14:45.576 --> 00:14:47.366 A:middle
your app in novel and

00:14:47.366 --> 00:14:48.306 A:middle
interesting ways.

00:14:48.836 --> 00:14:52.306 A:middle
To adopt CoreNFC, you need to

00:14:52.306 --> 00:14:54.116 A:middle
declare the corresponding

00:14:54.116 --> 00:14:55.926 A:middle
purpose string and provide the

00:14:55.926 --> 00:14:56.916 A:middle
necessary context.

00:14:57.716 --> 00:14:59.776 A:middle
And this purpose string will be

00:14:59.776 --> 00:15:01.386 A:middle
included in the prompt shown to

00:15:01.386 --> 00:15:03.826 A:middle
the user every time your app

00:15:04.186 --> 00:15:05.276 A:middle
invokes CoreNFC.

00:15:05.276 --> 00:15:08.536 A:middle
Now, let's talk about the watch.

00:15:09.636 --> 00:15:10.876 A:middle
We want your apps to be able to

00:15:10.876 --> 00:15:12.136 A:middle
do more with the watch.

00:15:12.546 --> 00:15:15.126 A:middle
So, this year we're expanding

00:15:15.426 --> 00:15:16.496 A:middle
the use of the microphone.

00:15:17.636 --> 00:15:21.466 A:middle
Today, in iOS 10, your app can

00:15:21.466 --> 00:15:24.036 A:middle
ask for microphone access and

00:15:24.156 --> 00:15:26.136 A:middle
following the users' consent, it

00:15:26.136 --> 00:15:28.756 A:middle
can start recording audio while

00:15:28.756 --> 00:15:29.536 A:middle
in the foreground.

00:15:30.376 --> 00:15:32.736 A:middle
In the new version watchOS, you

00:15:32.736 --> 00:15:34.886 A:middle
will be able to keep recording

00:15:35.336 --> 00:15:36.296 A:middle
while in the background.

00:15:37.046 --> 00:15:37.986 A:middle
And if you stay in the

00:15:38.046 --> 00:15:40.536 A:middle
foreground, you will be able to

00:15:40.806 --> 00:15:43.116 A:middle
use a new API to record audio

00:15:43.406 --> 00:15:47.706 A:middle
without showing the built-in UI.

00:15:47.886 --> 00:15:49.436 A:middle
Because we want users to always

00:15:49.436 --> 00:15:51.056 A:middle
be aware that their microphone

00:15:51.056 --> 00:15:53.646 A:middle
is active, if your app is in the

00:15:53.646 --> 00:15:55.356 A:middle
background, there will be an

00:15:55.356 --> 00:15:56.856 A:middle
indicator on the watch face.

00:15:57.046 --> 00:15:58.826 A:middle
And if the user taps on the

00:15:58.826 --> 00:16:00.796 A:middle
indicator, your app will go in

00:16:00.796 --> 00:16:01.286 A:middle
the foreground.

00:16:01.866 --> 00:16:04.886 A:middle
Let's talk about music.

00:16:06.496 --> 00:16:09.576 A:middle
We want your apps to be able to

00:16:09.576 --> 00:16:11.396 A:middle
take advantage of music and

00:16:11.396 --> 00:16:12.956 A:middle
create great features.

00:16:14.026 --> 00:16:16.936 A:middle
So, part of this experience is

00:16:17.456 --> 00:16:19.826 A:middle
having a frictionless way to

00:16:19.826 --> 00:16:21.746 A:middle
authenticate the user while

00:16:21.746 --> 00:16:22.806 A:middle
respecting their privacy.

00:16:23.436 --> 00:16:24.786 A:middle
So, for example if an app were

00:16:24.786 --> 00:16:26.536 A:middle
to ask for the user's password

00:16:26.686 --> 00:16:28.486 A:middle
to Music, that would be a

00:16:28.486 --> 00:16:29.376 A:middle
privacy concern.

00:16:30.756 --> 00:16:33.676 A:middle
Instead, apps should leverage

00:16:33.676 --> 00:16:35.106 A:middle
the fact that the users are

00:16:35.106 --> 00:16:37.326 A:middle
already signed into Music on

00:16:37.326 --> 00:16:37.776 A:middle
iOS.

00:16:38.326 --> 00:16:43.906 A:middle
And iOS has a built-in mediation

00:16:43.906 --> 00:16:46.336 A:middle
mechanism for giving your apps

00:16:46.376 --> 00:16:48.376 A:middle
access to Music with token.

00:16:49.386 --> 00:16:51.546 A:middle
Following the users consent, you

00:16:51.546 --> 00:16:53.606 A:middle
can get that token, and use it

00:16:53.606 --> 00:16:58.756 A:middle
to access output APIs to

00:16:59.656 --> 00:17:02.636 A:middle
retrieve personalized and

00:17:02.636 --> 00:17:04.116 A:middle
non-personalized information.

00:17:04.486 --> 00:17:07.216 A:middle
For example, search the iTunes

00:17:07.216 --> 00:17:09.716 A:middle
catalog, or get information

00:17:09.716 --> 00:17:10.846 A:middle
about the users' library.

00:17:11.336 --> 00:17:14.556 A:middle
And remember, because you have

00:17:14.556 --> 00:17:17.286 A:middle
control over which apps get this

00:17:17.286 --> 00:17:21.006 A:middle
token, make sure you provide the

00:17:21.006 --> 00:17:22.526 A:middle
necessary context in the purpose

00:17:22.596 --> 00:17:23.766 A:middle
string for the users to

00:17:23.766 --> 00:17:25.586 A:middle
understand what you're going to

00:17:25.586 --> 00:17:26.686 A:middle
do with it.

00:17:28.126 --> 00:17:29.676 A:middle
And now, let's talk about Safari

00:17:29.676 --> 00:17:30.136 A:middle
Controller.

00:17:30.816 --> 00:17:32.766 A:middle
Safari Controller is a great way

00:17:32.856 --> 00:17:34.246 A:middle
for users to browse the web in

00:17:34.246 --> 00:17:34.976 A:middle
your apps.

00:17:36.116 --> 00:17:39.986 A:middle
And in iOS 10, Safari cookies

00:17:40.296 --> 00:17:42.616 A:middle
and website data were available

00:17:42.646 --> 00:17:44.086 A:middle
in SVC instances.

00:17:44.166 --> 00:17:46.086 A:middle
In Safari, we consider instances

00:17:46.486 --> 00:17:47.236 A:middle
in your apps.

00:17:48.286 --> 00:17:49.446 A:middle
This will change.

00:17:50.386 --> 00:17:52.996 A:middle
Now, in iOS 11, users will be

00:17:52.996 --> 00:17:56.566 A:middle
able to use an account to log in

00:17:56.566 --> 00:17:57.826 A:middle
a website in your app.

00:17:58.416 --> 00:18:00.016 A:middle
And perhaps us a different

00:18:00.016 --> 00:18:01.806 A:middle
account if they want to, to log

00:18:01.806 --> 00:18:03.466 A:middle
into the same website in Safari,

00:18:03.796 --> 00:18:04.626 A:middle
or some other app.

00:18:05.936 --> 00:18:07.456 A:middle
And we think that gives users

00:18:07.456 --> 00:18:08.196 A:middle
more control.

00:18:08.966 --> 00:18:10.486 A:middle
Specifically, what this means is

00:18:10.486 --> 00:18:12.806 A:middle
that Safari, in Safari you

00:18:12.806 --> 00:18:14.846 A:middle
consider instances, will have

00:18:14.846 --> 00:18:17.496 A:middle
separate data stores for cookies

00:18:17.716 --> 00:18:18.736 A:middle
and other website's data.

00:18:19.816 --> 00:18:21.186 A:middle
And what this means for you and

00:18:21.186 --> 00:18:22.866 A:middle
your users is that they will

00:18:22.866 --> 00:18:24.936 A:middle
still be able to browse the web

00:18:24.986 --> 00:18:26.496 A:middle
in your app the same way as

00:18:26.496 --> 00:18:29.476 A:middle
before, but they may have to log

00:18:29.476 --> 00:18:31.336 A:middle
in again to some of the sites

00:18:31.416 --> 00:18:32.446 A:middle
they visit.

00:18:34.596 --> 00:18:36.486 A:middle
This is what it looks like.

00:18:37.016 --> 00:18:39.276 A:middle
So, for example, I have

00:18:39.346 --> 00:18:41.566 A:middle
Apple.com cookies in Safari, and

00:18:41.566 --> 00:18:44.006 A:middle
I have different cookies in your

00:18:44.276 --> 00:18:44.416 A:middle
app.

00:18:45.436 --> 00:18:48.226 A:middle
So, this concludes the updates.

00:18:48.586 --> 00:18:50.246 A:middle
At this point I would like to

00:18:50.246 --> 00:18:52.146 A:middle
invite Katie on stage to tell

00:18:52.146 --> 00:18:53.716 A:middle
you all about some exciting new

00:18:53.716 --> 00:18:55.546 A:middle
privacy features that Apple is

00:18:55.546 --> 00:18:56.266 A:middle
launching this year.

00:18:56.936 --> 00:18:57.206 A:middle
Katie.

00:18:58.516 --> 00:19:02.626 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:19:03.126 --> 00:19:04.186 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Georgios.

00:19:05.486 --> 00:19:06.656 A:middle
Now, I'm going to focus on some

00:19:06.656 --> 00:19:08.756 A:middle
new privacy features, as well as

00:19:08.756 --> 00:19:09.906 A:middle
provide an update on

00:19:09.906 --> 00:19:11.736 A:middle
differential privacy, that we

00:19:11.736 --> 00:19:12.826 A:middle
introduced last year.

00:19:12.826 --> 00:19:15.026 A:middle
I'm going to start with on

00:19:15.026 --> 00:19:16.126 A:middle
device processing.

00:19:16.886 --> 00:19:18.516 A:middle
Now, on device processing has a

00:19:18.516 --> 00:19:19.916 A:middle
lot of benefits.

00:19:20.056 --> 00:19:21.456 A:middle
One of the first ones is it

00:19:21.456 --> 00:19:23.696 A:middle
enables your functionality to

00:19:23.696 --> 00:19:25.586 A:middle
run anywhere your users are.

00:19:26.056 --> 00:19:27.136 A:middle
Whether they're at the beach,

00:19:27.206 --> 00:19:29.326 A:middle
like this, or on an airplane

00:19:29.326 --> 00:19:31.706 A:middle
flight or even in areas of poor

00:19:31.706 --> 00:19:33.226 A:middle
cellular connectivity.

00:19:34.496 --> 00:19:36.636 A:middle
It also avoids network latency.

00:19:36.636 --> 00:19:38.986 A:middle
As depending on where your users

00:19:38.986 --> 00:19:41.186 A:middle
are, this may take longer than

00:19:41.186 --> 00:19:42.786 A:middle
the actual processing that you

00:19:42.786 --> 00:19:43.836 A:middle
want to accomplish.

00:19:44.376 --> 00:19:47.126 A:middle
The speed of our devices, our

00:19:47.316 --> 00:19:49.506 A:middle
iPhones are iPads, it keeps

00:19:49.506 --> 00:19:51.256 A:middle
increasing and increasing.

00:19:52.526 --> 00:19:56.916 A:middle
The iPhone 7 is 120 times the

00:19:56.916 --> 00:19:58.916 A:middle
processing power of the original

00:19:58.916 --> 00:19:59.336 A:middle
iPhone.

00:20:00.746 --> 00:20:03.046 A:middle
So, think through the different

00:20:03.046 --> 00:20:04.566 A:middle
tasks that you once thought were

00:20:04.566 --> 00:20:06.986 A:middle
not feasible on device and you

00:20:06.986 --> 00:20:07.876 A:middle
should reconsider.

00:20:08.416 --> 00:20:11.136 A:middle
Now, as you all are at the

00:20:11.136 --> 00:20:12.776 A:middle
privacy session, I'm going to

00:20:12.776 --> 00:20:13.856 A:middle
talk a little bit more about the

00:20:13.966 --> 00:20:16.166 A:middle
privacy related benefits of on

00:20:16.166 --> 00:20:17.116 A:middle
device processing.

00:20:17.116 --> 00:20:20.636 A:middle
One of the first ones is access

00:20:20.636 --> 00:20:21.256 A:middle
to user data.

00:20:21.846 --> 00:20:23.546 A:middle
So, there are many different

00:20:23.546 --> 00:20:24.896 A:middle
types of sensitive data on

00:20:24.896 --> 00:20:25.356 A:middle
device.

00:20:26.016 --> 00:20:27.226 A:middle
And when you're clear to your

00:20:27.226 --> 00:20:29.556 A:middle
users about how you plan to use

00:20:29.556 --> 00:20:32.626 A:middle
that data, like for instance if

00:20:32.626 --> 00:20:34.486 A:middle
you tell your users that the

00:20:34.486 --> 00:20:36.656 A:middle
photo that you take, if you

00:20:36.656 --> 00:20:38.896 A:middle
apply a nice halo on it, maybe a

00:20:38.896 --> 00:20:40.916 A:middle
filter, that stays on their

00:20:40.916 --> 00:20:43.446 A:middle
devices until they choose to

00:20:43.446 --> 00:20:45.276 A:middle
share it with another user or

00:20:45.276 --> 00:20:46.566 A:middle
maybe back it up with you.

00:20:47.616 --> 00:20:49.046 A:middle
Then users are going to be more

00:20:49.046 --> 00:20:51.396 A:middle
likely to want to grant you

00:20:51.396 --> 00:20:52.476 A:middle
access to their data.

00:20:52.726 --> 00:20:54.216 A:middle
And feel more comfortable about

00:20:55.476 --> 00:20:55.596 A:middle
it.

00:20:55.976 --> 00:20:57.536 A:middle
On device, you can also take

00:20:57.536 --> 00:20:59.316 A:middle
advantage of all the different

00:20:59.356 --> 00:21:01.426 A:middle
security features that are built

00:21:01.426 --> 00:21:02.596 A:middle
into our platforms.

00:21:03.756 --> 00:21:05.566 A:middle
These are things like data

00:21:05.566 --> 00:21:08.196 A:middle
protection, the keychain that

00:21:08.196 --> 00:21:10.736 A:middle
allow you to more securely take

00:21:10.736 --> 00:21:12.926 A:middle
care of user data without you

00:21:12.926 --> 00:21:14.456 A:middle
having to implement it yourself.

00:21:14.456 --> 00:21:17.796 A:middle
Now in past developer sessions,

00:21:18.186 --> 00:21:19.736 A:middle
they're a great resource for you

00:21:19.736 --> 00:21:22.026 A:middle
to go and learn more about these

00:21:22.026 --> 00:21:23.026 A:middle
security features.

00:21:23.586 --> 00:21:25.106 A:middle
I would encourage you to go

00:21:25.106 --> 00:21:27.076 A:middle
check out "Protecting Secrets

00:21:27.076 --> 00:21:27.786 A:middle
with the Keychain."

00:21:27.846 --> 00:21:29.206 A:middle
It's a great place to start.

00:21:30.866 --> 00:21:33.036 A:middle
Now, when you're using and

00:21:33.036 --> 00:21:34.976 A:middle
keeping the data on device, that

00:21:34.976 --> 00:21:36.516 A:middle
means you don't have to write

00:21:36.676 --> 00:21:39.786 A:middle
code to send that data to your

00:21:39.786 --> 00:21:40.326 A:middle
server.

00:21:41.396 --> 00:21:43.306 A:middle
You don't have to write code to

00:21:43.306 --> 00:21:45.916 A:middle
securely manage and make sure

00:21:45.916 --> 00:21:47.946 A:middle
that that data on your server is

00:21:47.946 --> 00:21:48.456 A:middle
secure.

00:21:49.286 --> 00:21:51.786 A:middle
Now you all now the less code

00:21:51.786 --> 00:21:54.086 A:middle
you have to write, that means

00:21:54.196 --> 00:21:54.846 A:middle
the less bugs.

00:21:55.366 --> 00:21:58.116 A:middle
And the less bugs are less bugs

00:21:58.116 --> 00:21:59.336 A:middle
that an attacker can take

00:21:59.336 --> 00:22:00.086 A:middle
advantage of.

00:22:00.826 --> 00:22:02.776 A:middle
Because a data breach is very

00:22:02.836 --> 00:22:03.226 A:middle
serious.

00:22:03.226 --> 00:22:04.056 A:middle
And there are a lot of

00:22:04.056 --> 00:22:05.096 A:middle
consequences.

00:22:05.496 --> 00:22:07.436 A:middle
But one of the consequences is a

00:22:07.436 --> 00:22:09.346 A:middle
loss of user trust.

00:22:10.916 --> 00:22:13.416 A:middle
Now, technologies like this can

00:22:13.596 --> 00:22:15.566 A:middle
help you avoid that as well.

00:22:15.566 --> 00:22:18.876 A:middle
Now, I'm going to talk about

00:22:19.016 --> 00:22:21.736 A:middle
four new frameworks that allow

00:22:21.736 --> 00:22:24.376 A:middle
you to do these common tasks on

00:22:24.376 --> 00:22:24.826 A:middle
device.

00:22:25.546 --> 00:22:27.436 A:middle
Now, any type of processing that

00:22:27.436 --> 00:22:29.926 A:middle
you do within your app, you can

00:22:29.926 --> 00:22:30.956 A:middle
move to on device.

00:22:31.516 --> 00:22:32.666 A:middle
But here are four frameworks

00:22:32.716 --> 00:22:33.656 A:middle
that make it easier.

00:22:34.316 --> 00:22:36.536 A:middle
The first one is CoreML, Core

00:22:36.536 --> 00:22:37.336 A:middle
Machine Learning.

00:22:38.136 --> 00:22:40.296 A:middle
Now, this allows you to have a

00:22:40.376 --> 00:22:42.216 A:middle
simple interface to load and run

00:22:42.366 --> 00:22:43.306 A:middle
pretrained models.

00:22:44.096 --> 00:22:44.976 A:middle
There are a lot of different

00:22:44.976 --> 00:22:47.246 A:middle
models that it supports, but one

00:22:47.246 --> 00:22:48.396 A:middle
of them is neural networks.

00:22:48.696 --> 00:22:50.836 A:middle
The second framework I'm going

00:22:50.836 --> 00:22:52.106 A:middle
to talk about is VisionKit.

00:22:53.346 --> 00:22:54.756 A:middle
Now, VisionKit allows you to

00:22:54.756 --> 00:22:58.286 A:middle
identify faces within a photo as

00:22:58.286 --> 00:23:00.216 A:middle
well as do scene classification

00:23:01.156 --> 00:23:03.966 A:middle
and group photos by the contents

00:23:03.966 --> 00:23:05.276 A:middle
of the scene and time.

00:23:05.556 --> 00:23:08.316 A:middle
One of the ones that I'm most

00:23:08.316 --> 00:23:09.986 A:middle
excited about is ARKit.

00:23:10.196 --> 00:23:12.246 A:middle
I think augmented reality is a

00:23:12.246 --> 00:23:13.326 A:middle
place where there's lots of

00:23:13.326 --> 00:23:14.496 A:middle
exciting things to come.

00:23:14.496 --> 00:23:16.046 A:middle
And I can't wait to get it in

00:23:16.126 --> 00:23:17.916 A:middle
all of your hands to see what

00:23:17.916 --> 00:23:19.396 A:middle
kind of experiences you guys

00:23:19.716 --> 00:23:20.726 A:middle
create for our users.

00:23:21.896 --> 00:23:24.306 A:middle
Now, ARKit can allow you to

00:23:24.306 --> 00:23:26.666 A:middle
locate the device, as well as

00:23:26.666 --> 00:23:27.966 A:middle
items in the real world.

00:23:28.556 --> 00:23:29.926 A:middle
And then it allows you to

00:23:29.976 --> 00:23:31.966 A:middle
augment on top of the camera

00:23:32.026 --> 00:23:32.556 A:middle
stream.

00:23:33.846 --> 00:23:36.626 A:middle
Now, lastly we have NLP, Natural

00:23:36.626 --> 00:23:37.766 A:middle
Language Processing.

00:23:38.286 --> 00:23:39.856 A:middle
This allows you to identify what

00:23:39.856 --> 00:23:42.316 A:middle
language a customer may have, be

00:23:42.316 --> 00:23:43.236 A:middle
entering text within.

00:23:43.286 --> 00:23:45.486 A:middle
And it also allows you to do

00:23:45.486 --> 00:23:47.586 A:middle
tokenization as well as named

00:23:47.586 --> 00:23:49.096 A:middle
entity recognition.

00:23:49.866 --> 00:23:51.666 A:middle
Now, I'd encourage you to go

00:23:51.666 --> 00:23:53.616 A:middle
check out the talk, "Introducing

00:23:53.616 --> 00:23:56.566 A:middle
CoreML later this afternoon.

00:23:57.326 --> 00:23:59.416 A:middle
This will provide an overview of

00:23:59.416 --> 00:24:02.126 A:middle
the different features available

00:24:02.126 --> 00:24:03.466 A:middle
that you can take advantage of

00:24:03.556 --> 00:24:04.106 A:middle
on device.

00:24:04.726 --> 00:24:07.976 A:middle
Next, I'm going to talk about a

00:24:07.976 --> 00:24:11.516 A:middle
new framework available in iOS

00:24:11.746 --> 00:24:12.126 A:middle
and tvOS.

00:24:12.996 --> 00:24:13.986 A:middle
It's called DeviceCheck.

00:24:15.016 --> 00:24:16.856 A:middle
Now, there are many developers

00:24:17.116 --> 00:24:18.546 A:middle
who are currently using a

00:24:18.546 --> 00:24:20.676 A:middle
variety of techniques to try to

00:24:20.676 --> 00:24:21.876 A:middle
identify devices.

00:24:22.996 --> 00:24:24.386 A:middle
Now, they may be trying to

00:24:24.386 --> 00:24:26.226 A:middle
identify and answer questions

00:24:26.226 --> 00:24:28.716 A:middle
like, has this device received a

00:24:28.716 --> 00:24:29.376 A:middle
free trial?

00:24:30.236 --> 00:24:32.466 A:middle
Has this device participated in

00:24:32.466 --> 00:24:33.686 A:middle
fraudulent activity?

00:24:34.326 --> 00:24:36.846 A:middle
Or, has this advice done

00:24:36.846 --> 00:24:38.316 A:middle
something that is against your

00:24:38.316 --> 00:24:40.116 A:middle
apps developer guidelines?

00:24:41.326 --> 00:24:43.926 A:middle
Now, in order to achieve that

00:24:43.926 --> 00:24:46.156 A:middle
goal many developers, though I'm

00:24:46.156 --> 00:24:47.386 A:middle
sure none of you in this room,

00:24:47.776 --> 00:24:49.986 A:middle
may be collecting lots of

00:24:49.986 --> 00:24:51.336 A:middle
information in order to

00:24:51.336 --> 00:24:54.676 A:middle
associate some state with that

00:24:54.676 --> 00:24:55.046 A:middle
device.

00:24:55.046 --> 00:24:58.256 A:middle
Now, to do that they may be

00:24:58.256 --> 00:24:59.696 A:middle
collecting lots of information

00:24:59.696 --> 00:25:01.596 A:middle
like how is the device set up,

00:25:02.856 --> 00:25:04.266 A:middle
what information is stored on

00:25:05.916 --> 00:25:05.986 A:middle
it.

00:25:05.986 --> 00:25:07.496 A:middle
And these developers may not

00:25:07.496 --> 00:25:08.756 A:middle
want to have this level of

00:25:08.756 --> 00:25:09.536 A:middle
information.

00:25:10.696 --> 00:25:12.266 A:middle
All they want to do is associate

00:25:12.266 --> 00:25:13.926 A:middle
some state with that device in

00:25:13.926 --> 00:25:14.516 A:middle
particular.

00:25:16.626 --> 00:25:18.806 A:middle
Now, device check allows you to

00:25:18.806 --> 00:25:20.626 A:middle
associate state with the device.

00:25:21.266 --> 00:25:22.866 A:middle
And this is done in a privacy

00:25:22.936 --> 00:25:24.766 A:middle
friendly way, that you can

00:25:24.766 --> 00:25:26.186 A:middle
achieve without collecting

00:25:26.286 --> 00:25:27.996 A:middle
unnecessary information.

00:25:29.326 --> 00:25:30.676 A:middle
Now DeviceCheck allows you to

00:25:30.676 --> 00:25:33.006 A:middle
store 2 bits of information as

00:25:33.006 --> 00:25:35.046 A:middle
well as a timestamp associated

00:25:35.046 --> 00:25:36.046 A:middle
with one device.

00:25:36.566 --> 00:25:38.356 A:middle
And this is per team ID.

00:25:39.286 --> 00:25:45.396 A:middle
So, you can store 00, 01, 10, or

00:25:45.396 --> 00:25:45.816 A:middle
11.

00:25:46.656 --> 00:25:49.076 A:middle
And it's up to you to think

00:25:49.076 --> 00:25:52.966 A:middle
about what this means to your

00:25:53.056 --> 00:25:56.896 A:middle
application and your app logic.

00:25:57.046 --> 00:25:59.856 A:middle
Now, this information will be

00:25:59.856 --> 00:26:02.886 A:middle
maintained by Apple through,

00:26:03.246 --> 00:26:05.646 A:middle
until you reset it, or you

00:26:05.646 --> 00:26:06.526 A:middle
update the state.

00:26:07.236 --> 00:26:08.766 A:middle
So, this means it will be stored

00:26:08.766 --> 00:26:10.796 A:middle
by Apple through deletion of

00:26:11.406 --> 00:26:13.116 A:middle
your app, re-instillation of

00:26:13.116 --> 00:26:15.256 A:middle
your app, through erase all

00:26:15.256 --> 00:26:17.606 A:middle
contents and settings, as well

00:26:18.166 --> 00:26:20.046 A:middle
as transfer of that device

00:26:20.116 --> 00:26:20.946 A:middle
between users.

00:26:21.596 --> 00:26:23.436 A:middle
Now, we know users sell devices

00:26:23.436 --> 00:26:23.906 A:middle
to others.

00:26:24.256 --> 00:26:25.946 A:middle
We know they transfer them to

00:26:25.946 --> 00:26:27.496 A:middle
other siblings, or other people

00:26:27.496 --> 00:26:27.956 A:middle
they know.

00:26:28.366 --> 00:26:29.756 A:middle
So, this information will be

00:26:29.756 --> 00:26:30.776 A:middle
maintained through that.

00:26:32.466 --> 00:26:34.046 A:middle
Now, as I mentioned before, it's

00:26:34.046 --> 00:26:36.286 A:middle
up to you figure out what these

00:26:36.286 --> 00:26:37.246 A:middle
states mean to you.

00:26:37.246 --> 00:26:40.686 A:middle
So, an example would be for app

00:26:40.686 --> 00:26:42.536 A:middle
A, if a user has completed a

00:26:42.616 --> 00:26:44.566 A:middle
free trial, they will be

00:26:44.566 --> 00:26:46.126 A:middle
assigned state 01.

00:26:47.186 --> 00:26:48.606 A:middle
Now, you can have a different

00:26:48.816 --> 00:26:50.686 A:middle
app, app B, and that same

00:26:50.746 --> 00:26:52.376 A:middle
information, that same state

00:26:52.376 --> 00:26:53.426 A:middle
that a free trial has been

00:26:53.426 --> 00:26:55.516 A:middle
assigned or completed, could be

00:26:55.516 --> 00:26:56.596 A:middle
assigned 11.

00:26:57.556 --> 00:26:58.646 A:middle
It's up to you to make that

00:26:58.646 --> 00:26:59.126 A:middle
decision.

00:26:59.126 --> 00:27:01.786 A:middle
Now, I want to go through the

00:27:01.786 --> 00:27:02.946 A:middle
flow and make sure you guys

00:27:02.946 --> 00:27:05.466 A:middle
understand how this works in

00:27:05.466 --> 00:27:06.096 A:middle
practice.

00:27:07.026 --> 00:27:07.946 A:middle
So, let's say there's an app

00:27:08.356 --> 00:27:09.486 A:middle
that's a news app.

00:27:09.486 --> 00:27:11.346 A:middle
And like I said before it grants

00:27:11.346 --> 00:27:12.766 A:middle
a 7-day free trial.

00:27:13.516 --> 00:27:15.856 A:middle
So, when my free trial is

00:27:15.896 --> 00:27:18.116 A:middle
completed, the app wants to set

00:27:18.296 --> 00:27:19.896 A:middle
my state, to 01.

00:27:20.556 --> 00:27:21.756 A:middle
So, first thing it's going to do

00:27:21.756 --> 00:27:23.286 A:middle
is query for a device check

00:27:23.386 --> 00:27:24.226 A:middle
token on device.

00:27:25.256 --> 00:27:27.406 A:middle
Send it to their app server and

00:27:27.406 --> 00:27:28.576 A:middle
then via server to server

00:27:28.576 --> 00:27:30.726 A:middle
communication, set the state and

00:27:30.726 --> 00:27:31.406 A:middle
send it to Apple.

00:27:32.026 --> 00:27:33.556 A:middle
So, send over the token and the

00:27:33.556 --> 00:27:36.916 A:middle
state that wants to be set.

00:27:36.916 --> 00:27:40.226 A:middle
So, then I decide, maybe I'm not

00:27:40.226 --> 00:27:41.506 A:middle
a huge fan of that news app

00:27:41.506 --> 00:27:41.846 A:middle
anymore.

00:27:42.426 --> 00:27:44.106 A:middle
I want to delete it.

00:27:44.386 --> 00:27:46.296 A:middle
But then I miss it a couple

00:27:46.296 --> 00:27:47.946 A:middle
weeks later, so I decide I'm

00:27:48.056 --> 00:27:49.946 A:middle
going to reinstall the app.

00:27:50.046 --> 00:27:52.026 A:middle
On launch, that app wants to

00:27:52.026 --> 00:27:54.726 A:middle
decide should I be giving that

00:27:54.726 --> 00:27:56.596 A:middle
user, or that device be given

00:27:56.596 --> 00:27:57.586 A:middle
another free trial?

00:27:58.686 --> 00:28:01.236 A:middle
So, query for the token, send it

00:28:01.236 --> 00:28:02.766 A:middle
to App Server the same way and

00:28:02.766 --> 00:28:04.546 A:middle
this time, query for the state

00:28:04.546 --> 00:28:05.346 A:middle
of the device.

00:28:06.326 --> 00:28:10.446 A:middle
So, then because that device was

00:28:10.446 --> 00:28:12.856 A:middle
last set as 01, it will be sent

00:28:12.856 --> 00:28:13.816 A:middle
back to the app server.

00:28:13.926 --> 00:28:15.456 A:middle
And at that point, it's the

00:28:15.456 --> 00:28:17.046 A:middle
app's job to figure out what to

00:28:17.046 --> 00:28:17.266 A:middle
do next.

00:28:18.326 --> 00:28:19.936 A:middle
Should that device be granted

00:28:19.936 --> 00:28:20.906 A:middle
another free trial?

00:28:21.756 --> 00:28:23.826 A:middle
Should that device be granted

00:28:23.826 --> 00:28:26.046 A:middle
maybe a shorter trial, or no

00:28:26.046 --> 00:28:26.666 A:middle
trial at all?

00:28:27.016 --> 00:28:29.386 A:middle
It's up to you to make that

00:28:31.316 --> 00:28:31.556 A:middle
decision.

00:28:31.646 --> 00:28:34.126 A:middle
So, as I said before, devices

00:28:34.126 --> 00:28:35.576 A:middle
can transfer between users.

00:28:36.316 --> 00:28:37.776 A:middle
So, let's say I sell my device

00:28:37.776 --> 00:28:38.866 A:middle
to Georgios, because I want a

00:28:38.866 --> 00:28:39.316 A:middle
different phone.

00:28:39.856 --> 00:28:41.776 A:middle
I want a new gold one this time.

00:28:42.496 --> 00:28:45.126 A:middle
So, then Georgios wants to

00:28:45.126 --> 00:28:46.036 A:middle
install the same app.

00:28:46.036 --> 00:28:47.306 A:middle
He likes the same news app.

00:28:47.796 --> 00:28:49.086 A:middle
So, it's going to query for the

00:28:49.086 --> 00:28:51.036 A:middle
token the same way, send it to

00:28:51.036 --> 00:28:51.816 A:middle
its app server.

00:28:52.476 --> 00:28:54.146 A:middle
And then query for the state.

00:28:55.076 --> 00:28:57.426 A:middle
Again, 01 will be returned.

00:28:58.366 --> 00:29:00.526 A:middle
And in this case Georgios has

00:29:00.526 --> 00:29:01.896 A:middle
not bought a free trial.

00:29:02.176 --> 00:29:03.366 A:middle
So, you need to think about how

00:29:03.366 --> 00:29:04.836 A:middle
to handle these type of cases.

00:29:06.006 --> 00:29:08.486 A:middle
Now, make sure that you have a

00:29:08.486 --> 00:29:09.926 A:middle
way that customers can reach

00:29:09.926 --> 00:29:12.676 A:middle
out, or escalate if they are

00:29:12.676 --> 00:29:14.236 A:middle
experiencing issues with this.

00:29:14.236 --> 00:29:16.026 A:middle
And they need to come and reach

00:29:16.026 --> 00:29:18.406 A:middle
out to you, because at Apple we

00:29:18.406 --> 00:29:20.576 A:middle
don't have any idea what these

00:29:20.576 --> 00:29:21.756 A:middle
states correspond to.

00:29:21.956 --> 00:29:25.346 A:middle
So, now I'm going to quickly go

00:29:25.346 --> 00:29:26.636 A:middle
through what a sample query can

00:29:26.636 --> 00:29:26.956 A:middle
look like.

00:29:28.086 --> 00:29:29.026 A:middle
As you can see, here's the

00:29:29.026 --> 00:29:31.236 A:middle
device token, the transaction

00:29:31.236 --> 00:29:33.336 A:middle
ID, which you generate, as well

00:29:33.336 --> 00:29:33.996 A:middle
as a timestamp.

00:29:35.086 --> 00:29:36.736 A:middle
Then, here's the response from

00:29:36.736 --> 00:29:37.906 A:middle
Apple, with the state.

00:29:38.606 --> 00:29:41.416 A:middle
And then, if you want to update

00:29:41.416 --> 00:29:42.966 A:middle
the state, again, have the

00:29:42.966 --> 00:29:46.346 A:middle
device token, your transaction

00:29:46.346 --> 00:29:48.226 A:middle
ID that you generate, as well as

00:29:48.226 --> 00:29:49.306 A:middle
the timestamp and the state you

00:29:49.306 --> 00:29:51.756 A:middle
want to set.

00:29:51.986 --> 00:29:53.346 A:middle
When you're using DeviceCheck,

00:29:53.626 --> 00:29:55.096 A:middle
make sure to think through these

00:29:55.096 --> 00:29:55.926 A:middle
best practices.

00:29:57.136 --> 00:29:58.646 A:middle
Make sure you handle the case

00:29:58.856 --> 00:30:00.306 A:middle
where devices are transferred

00:30:00.406 --> 00:30:01.096 A:middle
between users.

00:30:02.056 --> 00:30:04.696 A:middle
A devices' behavior can change

00:30:04.696 --> 00:30:05.376 A:middle
over time.

00:30:06.846 --> 00:30:08.046 A:middle
Additionally, think about the

00:30:08.046 --> 00:30:09.056 A:middle
recency of the data.

00:30:10.166 --> 00:30:11.886 A:middle
If the state was set a year ago,

00:30:12.526 --> 00:30:13.516 A:middle
maybe that means something

00:30:13.516 --> 00:30:15.196 A:middle
different to you than if it was

00:30:15.196 --> 00:30:15.816 A:middle
this month.

00:30:17.466 --> 00:30:18.936 A:middle
They should be part of your apps

00:30:18.936 --> 00:30:21.106 A:middle
logic, but not the sole source.

00:30:21.826 --> 00:30:23.486 A:middle
And think of how you represent

00:30:23.486 --> 00:30:24.396 A:middle
this state in the UI.

00:30:25.436 --> 00:30:26.796 A:middle
When Georgios goes to launch the

00:30:26.796 --> 00:30:28.296 A:middle
app for the first time, you want

00:30:28.296 --> 00:30:29.686 A:middle
to have a fresh experience for

00:30:29.686 --> 00:30:29.976 A:middle
him.

00:30:30.796 --> 00:30:31.786 A:middle
So, make sure you think through

00:30:32.436 --> 00:30:32.526 A:middle
that.

00:30:33.306 --> 00:30:35.576 A:middle
Now, you should be using

00:30:35.656 --> 00:30:37.856 A:middle
platform supported identifiers.

00:30:38.746 --> 00:30:39.876 A:middle
These are the application

00:30:39.876 --> 00:30:41.576 A:middle
identifier, the vendor

00:30:41.576 --> 00:30:43.116 A:middle
identifier, as well as the

00:30:43.116 --> 00:30:44.456 A:middle
advertising identifier.

00:30:45.676 --> 00:30:47.306 A:middle
We will continue to remove

00:30:47.406 --> 00:30:50.546 A:middle
entropy out of the app sandbox.

00:30:50.906 --> 00:30:53.026 A:middle
And as we have before, we will

00:30:53.026 --> 00:30:54.566 A:middle
continue to identify areas of

00:30:54.566 --> 00:30:57.486 A:middle
entropy and put them either

00:30:57.556 --> 00:30:59.146 A:middle
behind user control or remove

00:30:59.146 --> 00:30:59.436 A:middle
them.

00:30:59.946 --> 00:31:03.896 A:middle
Next, I'm going to talk about

00:31:04.456 --> 00:31:06.076 A:middle
intelligent tracking protection.

00:31:07.006 --> 00:31:08.096 A:middle
This year we're working to

00:31:08.096 --> 00:31:10.466 A:middle
reduce cross web tracking.

00:31:10.966 --> 00:31:14.156 A:middle
Now since the beginning WebKit

00:31:14.156 --> 00:31:15.626 A:middle
and Safari have been leaders in

00:31:15.626 --> 00:31:16.516 A:middle
user privacy.

00:31:17.746 --> 00:31:19.246 A:middle
One example of this is blocking

00:31:19.246 --> 00:31:20.936 A:middle
third-party cookies by default.

00:31:22.326 --> 00:31:23.756 A:middle
Now, I want to get this out

00:31:23.756 --> 00:31:25.236 A:middle
there that intelligent tracking

00:31:25.236 --> 00:31:26.796 A:middle
protection is not about blocking

00:31:26.796 --> 00:31:27.226 A:middle
content.

00:31:27.506 --> 00:31:28.796 A:middle
That's not what this technology

00:31:30.426 --> 00:31:30.536 A:middle
is.

00:31:31.376 --> 00:31:33.016 A:middle
It dynamically detects online

00:31:33.016 --> 00:31:34.916 A:middle
tracking across the sites that a

00:31:34.916 --> 00:31:35.786 A:middle
user visits.

00:31:36.346 --> 00:31:37.786 A:middle
And using an on device

00:31:37.876 --> 00:31:39.756 A:middle
classifier, it will identify

00:31:39.756 --> 00:31:40.756 A:middle
tracking domains.

00:31:41.386 --> 00:31:42.606 A:middle
Once a tracking domain is

00:31:42.606 --> 00:31:45.116 A:middle
identified, then it will isolate

00:31:45.346 --> 00:31:47.246 A:middle
the third-party cookies as well

00:31:47.246 --> 00:31:49.656 A:middle
as website data for that

00:31:49.656 --> 00:31:49.966 A:middle
website.

00:31:49.966 --> 00:31:52.456 A:middle
And then periodically that data

00:31:52.456 --> 00:31:53.376 A:middle
will be purged.

00:31:54.656 --> 00:31:56.306 A:middle
Note, if the user interacts with

00:31:56.306 --> 00:31:58.306 A:middle
that domain, that is taken as a

00:31:58.346 --> 00:31:59.726 A:middle
signal that the user is

00:31:59.726 --> 00:32:01.096 A:middle
interested in that website and

00:32:01.556 --> 00:32:03.226 A:middle
then that website will be white

00:32:03.226 --> 00:32:03.686 A:middle
listed.

00:32:04.656 --> 00:32:05.856 A:middle
So, let's go through an example.

00:32:06.856 --> 00:32:10.116 A:middle
So, if example.com is identified

00:32:10.116 --> 00:32:11.746 A:middle
as a tracker, and the user

00:32:11.746 --> 00:32:13.666 A:middle
visits site one, that embeds

00:32:13.666 --> 00:32:16.046 A:middle
example.com, example.com will

00:32:16.046 --> 00:32:16.986 A:middle
set the cookie foo.

00:32:18.036 --> 00:32:20.256 A:middle
Now, a user gores to site two,

00:32:20.606 --> 00:32:22.386 A:middle
which also embeds example.com,

00:32:22.846 --> 00:32:25.066 A:middle
but here example.com does not

00:32:25.066 --> 00:32:26.176 A:middle
have access to the cookie, foo.

00:32:26.176 --> 00:32:28.666 A:middle
So, then it will set cookie bar.

00:32:29.576 --> 00:32:31.596 A:middle
And then over time, these

00:32:31.596 --> 00:32:34.186 A:middle
cookies will be purged.

00:32:35.366 --> 00:32:37.986 A:middle
Now, no cookies will be deleted

00:32:37.986 --> 00:32:39.526 A:middle
from first party websites.

00:32:40.366 --> 00:32:41.496 A:middle
Additionally, if the user

00:32:41.496 --> 00:32:42.996 A:middle
interacts with your website, via

00:32:42.996 --> 00:32:46.066 A:middle
a click, a tap, entering a form

00:32:46.656 --> 00:32:50.396 A:middle
then it will be white listed.

00:32:50.646 --> 00:32:53.066 A:middle
You should not rely on storage

00:32:53.696 --> 00:32:55.316 A:middle
if the user does not interact

00:32:55.386 --> 00:32:56.306 A:middle
with your website.

00:32:56.306 --> 00:32:59.456 A:middle
And this is an important one to

00:32:59.456 --> 00:33:00.326 A:middle
understand.

00:33:00.746 --> 00:33:02.916 A:middle
If your analytics package relies

00:33:02.916 --> 00:33:06.066 A:middle
on third-party cookies, they may

00:33:06.066 --> 00:33:07.330 A:middle
be affected.

00:33:08.476 --> 00:33:10.296 A:middle
So, what we're trying to achieve

00:33:10.296 --> 00:33:12.686 A:middle
here is that users only have

00:33:12.686 --> 00:33:14.606 A:middle
long-term persistent tracking

00:33:14.986 --> 00:33:16.746 A:middle
and cookies from sites that they

00:33:16.746 --> 00:33:18.276 A:middle
actually intersect with.

00:33:18.546 --> 00:33:21.126 A:middle
The actually interact with.

00:33:21.126 --> 00:33:22.926 A:middle
And then all the other tracking

00:33:23.096 --> 00:33:24.826 A:middle
as the user navigates and visits

00:33:24.826 --> 00:33:27.116 A:middle
websites will be proactively

00:33:27.666 --> 00:33:27.846 A:middle
removed.

00:33:29.576 --> 00:33:31.846 A:middle
Lastly, we have an update on

00:33:31.846 --> 00:33:33.036 A:middle
differential privacy.

00:33:33.646 --> 00:33:36.026 A:middle
So, differential privacy was

00:33:36.026 --> 00:33:38.996 A:middle
launched on iOS and macOS last

00:33:38.996 --> 00:33:39.116 A:middle
year.

00:33:39.856 --> 00:33:42.176 A:middle
Since then, we've collected

00:33:42.176 --> 00:33:44.456 A:middle
millions of privately donated

00:33:44.456 --> 00:33:47.536 A:middle
data per day and it allowed us

00:33:47.576 --> 00:33:49.336 A:middle
to build user features with

00:33:49.366 --> 00:33:49.886 A:middle
privacy.

00:33:49.886 --> 00:33:53.576 A:middle
Now, I want to talk about two

00:33:53.576 --> 00:33:54.806 A:middle
new use cases this year.

00:33:55.606 --> 00:33:58.876 A:middle
The first one is collecting what

00:33:58.956 --> 00:34:00.856 A:middle
data is commonly stored in

00:34:00.856 --> 00:34:01.376 A:middle
HealthKit.

00:34:02.096 --> 00:34:04.216 A:middle
Now, one challenges of working

00:34:04.216 --> 00:34:06.016 A:middle
on sensitive features or

00:34:06.016 --> 00:34:07.376 A:middle
features that have sensitive

00:34:07.376 --> 00:34:09.566 A:middle
data is you want to understand

00:34:09.626 --> 00:34:10.936 A:middle
how those features are being

00:34:10.936 --> 00:34:11.396 A:middle
used.

00:34:12.266 --> 00:34:13.536 A:middle
You want to understand what's

00:34:13.536 --> 00:34:15.136 A:middle
resonating, where users are

00:34:15.136 --> 00:34:16.866 A:middle
falling into issues, or errors

00:34:16.866 --> 00:34:17.506 A:middle
are occurring.

00:34:17.936 --> 00:34:19.466 A:middle
But you know that collecting

00:34:19.466 --> 00:34:21.956 A:middle
data about what they're actually

00:34:21.956 --> 00:34:23.626 A:middle
interacting with may have more

00:34:23.626 --> 00:34:24.676 A:middle
information than you really

00:34:24.676 --> 00:34:24.996 A:middle
need.

00:34:25.836 --> 00:34:28.076 A:middle
So, one example here is if you

00:34:28.076 --> 00:34:30.296 A:middle
collect what type of data, what

00:34:30.296 --> 00:34:32.666 A:middle
data types the user has stored

00:34:32.666 --> 00:34:34.716 A:middle
on their device, things like

00:34:34.716 --> 00:34:36.256 A:middle
blood glucose, things like

00:34:36.326 --> 00:34:38.656 A:middle
workout that could convey other

00:34:38.656 --> 00:34:40.686 A:middle
additional information about

00:34:40.946 --> 00:34:43.236 A:middle
their health, or about any

00:34:43.236 --> 00:34:44.686 A:middle
conditions they have, or how

00:34:44.686 --> 00:34:45.366 A:middle
active they are.

00:34:45.366 --> 00:34:47.056 A:middle
And we don't really need that

00:34:47.056 --> 00:34:48.116 A:middle
level of information.

00:34:48.836 --> 00:34:50.056 A:middle
So, that's why it's so exciting

00:34:50.056 --> 00:34:51.386 A:middle
to have differential privacy at

00:34:51.386 --> 00:34:53.736 A:middle
Apple because we can still get

00:34:53.736 --> 00:34:55.246 A:middle
information to continue to

00:34:55.246 --> 00:34:57.246 A:middle
iterate and build our features,

00:34:57.526 --> 00:34:59.306 A:middle
while respecting user privacy.

00:34:59.826 --> 00:35:02.806 A:middle
So, last year in the privacy

00:35:02.806 --> 00:35:04.056 A:middle
session and developer

00:35:04.056 --> 00:35:05.866 A:middle
conference, Julian did a great

00:35:05.866 --> 00:35:07.476 A:middle
job deep diving into how

00:35:07.476 --> 00:35:08.956 A:middle
differential privacy works at

00:35:08.956 --> 00:35:09.236 A:middle
Apple.

00:35:10.756 --> 00:35:13.406 A:middle
Basically, we collect privatized

00:35:13.406 --> 00:35:16.426 A:middle
donations like emoji, and as

00:35:16.426 --> 00:35:18.116 A:middle
more and more users contribute

00:35:18.116 --> 00:35:19.896 A:middle
these privatized emojis, we

00:35:19.896 --> 00:35:20.726 A:middle
learned what are the most

00:35:20.766 --> 00:35:22.666 A:middle
popular emojis.

00:35:23.656 --> 00:35:25.766 A:middle
But, the key part here is we

00:35:25.766 --> 00:35:26.776 A:middle
learned nothing that's

00:35:26.886 --> 00:35:28.536 A:middle
associated about an individual

00:35:28.536 --> 00:35:28.956 A:middle
user.

00:35:29.966 --> 00:35:31.416 A:middle
For more information about how

00:35:31.416 --> 00:35:32.726 A:middle
differential privacy works at

00:35:32.726 --> 00:35:34.146 A:middle
Apple, I would encourage you all

00:35:34.146 --> 00:35:36.346 A:middle
to look at our session from last

00:35:36.346 --> 00:35:37.486 A:middle
year's developers conference.

00:35:39.066 --> 00:35:42.256 A:middle
So, this year we're applying the

00:35:42.256 --> 00:35:44.096 A:middle
same process to health data

00:35:44.096 --> 00:35:44.446 A:middle
types.

00:35:45.096 --> 00:35:46.416 A:middle
So, we will learn the most

00:35:46.416 --> 00:35:48.376 A:middle
popular health data types, but

00:35:48.376 --> 00:35:49.606 A:middle
with learning nothing about the

00:35:49.606 --> 00:35:50.696 A:middle
individual user.

00:35:51.296 --> 00:35:56.976 A:middle
The second case is trying to

00:35:57.026 --> 00:35:59.826 A:middle
learn websites that either are

00:35:59.826 --> 00:36:02.356 A:middle
very slow, or take up a lot of

00:36:02.356 --> 00:36:03.216 A:middle
battery life.

00:36:03.966 --> 00:36:05.976 A:middle
We all want a fast, speedy web,

00:36:06.586 --> 00:36:08.646 A:middle
but we don't necessarily want to

00:36:08.646 --> 00:36:11.456 A:middle
learn everything that a user is

00:36:11.456 --> 00:36:11.986 A:middle
visiting.

00:36:12.406 --> 00:36:13.886 A:middle
That's a lot of information

00:36:13.926 --> 00:36:15.596 A:middle
about that user depending on

00:36:15.696 --> 00:36:16.516 A:middle
their web searches.

00:36:17.276 --> 00:36:18.476 A:middle
So, this is another example

00:36:18.476 --> 00:36:19.786 A:middle
where we get to use differential

00:36:19.786 --> 00:36:21.796 A:middle
privacy to then reach out to

00:36:21.796 --> 00:36:23.756 A:middle
these developers who maybe had

00:36:23.756 --> 00:36:25.946 A:middle
issues or writing slow sites so

00:36:25.946 --> 00:36:27.256 A:middle
then we can improve the web for

00:36:27.256 --> 00:36:27.726 A:middle
everyone.

00:36:29.956 --> 00:36:33.666 A:middle
Now, in summary, we are all here

00:36:33.666 --> 00:36:36.256 A:middle
